{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510905"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:35:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:35:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11660"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11660"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.16,0.36,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4281"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112455"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4281"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11660"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94486"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"214"},{"type":"tags","id":"2036"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5756"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6730"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13084"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46122"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112455"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a eight-month history of a painless swelling in the left side of his scrotum. There has been no recent change in size of the swelling. He has no other symptoms. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The left testicle is slightly larger than the right testicle and is lower in the scrotum. Both testes feel firm and smooth. No other abnormalities are palpated in the scrotum. The left scrotal swelling transilluminates with a penlight torch. The remainder of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance","Review in six months","Ultrasound of the scrotum","Serum \u03b1-fetoprotein","Referral to urology"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of a unilateral, painless scrotal swelling that transilluminates is strongly suggestive of a hydrocele. A hydrocele is a collection of serous fluid between the layers of the tunica vaginalis. On examination, the testis may feel like a fluid-filled balloon, depending on the size of the hydrocele.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn an adult, hydroceles are generally benign and the mainstay of management is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance\u003C/strong\u003E and observation. The patient can self-monitor the hydrocele and does not require scheduled \u003Cstrong\u003Ereview\u003C/strong\u003E unless there are new concerns. Hydroceles may remain stable in size or gradually enlarge over time. They can also self resolve in some cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound of the scrotum\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated if the underlying testis cannot be palpated or if there are concerning features such as severe pain or systemic symptoms. While a hydrocele can be associated with underlying testicular pathology, in this case the testes feel normal and the patient is not in the age group where testicular tumours are most common. In addition, the swelling has been present and unchanged for eight months, so a malignant process is very unlikely. In a younger patient, an ultrasound would be advised to exclude an underlying testicular malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum \u03b1-fetoprotein\u003C/strong\u003E is a tumour marker used in the diagnosis and monitoring of testicular cancer. In the absence of concerning features suggestive of malignancy, this test is not currently indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral to urology\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary for a hydrocele unless it becomes extremely large or symptomatic, in which case surgical removal may be considered. This is not the case in the presented scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to management in this case is recognising the typical presentation of a hydrocele and providing appropriate reassurance to the patient. Examination findings such as transillumination support the diagnosis. In the absence of concerning features, conservative management with observation is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydroceles can be managed conservatively with reassurance and observation in adults if there are no concerning features.","Transillumination of a scrotal swelling is a key examination finding that supports the diagnosis of a hydrocele.","Scrotal ultrasound is indicated if the underlying testis cannot be palpated or if there are concerning features such as severe pain or systemic symptoms."],"references":["Hoang VT, Van HAT, Hoang TH, Nguyen TTT, Trinh CT. A Review of Classification, Diagnosis, and Management of Hydrocele. J Ultrasound Med. 2024 Mar;43(3):599-607. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38010662/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94486"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11660"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94486"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-01T10:47:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-01T10:48:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4281"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112455"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups",